    {
      "type": "Section",
      "title": "Quick Glossary",
      "content": "Quick Glossary",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 17,
        "level": 1
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "This quick glossary contains many of the terms used in relation to bitcoin. These terms are used throughout the book, so bookmark this for a quick reference and clarification.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 17,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*address (aka public key)*\n\nA bitcoin address looks like 1DSrfJdB2AnWaFNgSbv3MZC2m74996JafV - they consist of a string of letters and numbers starting with a \"1\" (number one). Just like you ask others to send an email to your email address, you would ask others to send you bitcoin to your bitcoin address.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 17,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*bip*\n\nBitcoin Improvement Proposals. A set of proposals that members of the bitcoin community have submitted to improve bitcoin. For example BIP0021 is a proposal to improve the bitcoin URI scheme.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 17,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*bitcoin*\n\nThe name of the currency unit (the coin), the network and the software",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 17,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*block*\n\nA grouping of transactions, marked with a timestamp, and a fingerprint of the previous block. The block header is hashed to find a proof-of-work, thereby validating the transactions. Valid blocks are added to the main blockchain by network consensus.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 17,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*blockchain*\n\nA list of validated blocks, each linking to its predecessor all the way to the genesis block.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 17,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*confirmations*\n\nOnce a transaction is included in a block, it has \"one confirmation\". As soon as another block is mined on the same blockchain, the transaction has two confirmations etc. Six or more confirmations is considered sufficient proof that a transaction cannot be reversed.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 17,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*difficulty*\n\nA network-wide setting that controls how much computation is required to find a proof-of-work.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 17,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*difficulty target*\n\nA difficulty at which all the computation in the network will find blocks approximately every 10 minutes.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 17,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*difficulty re-targeting*\n\nA network-wide re-calculation of the difficulty which occurs once every 2106 blocks and considers the hashing power of the previous 2106 blocks.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 17,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*fees*\n\nThe sender of a transaction often includes a fee to the network for processing their requested transaction. Most transactions require a minimum fee of 0.5mBTC.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 18,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*hash*\n\nA digital fingerprint of some binary input.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 18,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*genesis block*\n\nThe first block in the blockchain, used to initialize the crypto-currency",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 18,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*miner*\n\nA network node that finds valid proof-of-work for new blocks, by repeated hashing",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 18,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*network*\n\nA peer-to-peer network that propagates transactions and blocks to every bitcoin node on the network.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 18,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*proof-of-work*\n\nA piece of data that requires significant computation to find. In bitcoin, miners must find a numeric solution to the SHA256 algorithm that meets a network wide target, the difficulty target.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 18,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*reward*\n\nAn amount included in each new block as a reward by the network to the miner who found the proof-of-work solution. It is currently 25BTC per block.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 18,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*secret key (aka private key)*\n\nThe secret number that unlocks bitcoins sent to the corresponding address. A secret key looks like 5J76sF8L5jTtzE96r66Sf8cka9y44wdpJjMwCxR3tzLh3ibVPxh",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 18,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*transaction*\n\nIn simple terms, a transfer of bitcoins from one address to another. More precisely, a transaction is a signed data structure expressing a transfer of value. Transactions are transmitted over the bitcoin network, collected by miners and included into blocks, made permanent on the blockchain.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 18,
        "level": 2
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Paragraph",
      "content": "*wallet*\n\nSoftware that holds all your bitcoin addresses and secret keys. Use it to send, receive and store your bitcoin.",
      "metadata": {
        "page": 18,
        "level": 2
      }
    }
  ]
